{"title_page": "1931 Tour de France", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox cycling race report\n| name               = 1931 Tour de France\n| image              = Tour de France 1931.png\n| image_caption      = Route of the 1931 Tour de France followed counterclockwise, starting in Paris\n| image_alt          = \n| image_size         = 300px\n| date               = 30 June \u2013 26 July\n| stages             = 24\n| distance           = 5091\n| unit               = km\n| time               = 177h 10' 03\"\n| first              = [[Antonin Magne]]\n| first_nat          = FRA\n| first_color        = yellow\n| first_team         = France\n| second             = [[Jef Demuysere]]\n| second_nat         = BEL\n| second_team        = Belgium\n| third              = [[Antonio Pesenti]]\n| third_nat          = ITA\n| third_natvar       = 1861\n| third_team         = Italy\n| team               = Belgium\n| previous           = [[1930 Tour de France|1930]]\n| next               = [[1932 Tour de France|1932]]\n}}\nThe '''1931 Tour de France''' was the 25th edition of the [[Tour de France]], which took place from 30 June to 26 July. It consisted of 24 stages over {{convert|5091|km|0|abbr=on}}.\n\nThe race was won by French cyclist [[Antonin Magne]]. The sprinters [[Charles P\u00e9lissier]] and [[Rafaele di Paco]] both won five stages.<ref name=\"letour.fr\">{{cite web|url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/1931/histoire.html|title=The Tour - year 1931|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|accessdate=30 September 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090716153323/http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/1931/histoire.html|archive-date=16 July 2009|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe cyclists were separated into national teams and ''touriste-routiers'', who were grouped into regional teams. In some stages (2, 3, 4, 6, 7 and 12), the national teams started 10 minutes before the touriste-routiers.<ref name=\"mdc1931\"/>\n\nOne of these ''touriste-routiers'' was Max Bulla. In the second stage, when the ''touriste-routiers'' started 10 minutes later than the national teams, Bulla overtook the national teams, won the stage and took the lead, the only time in history that a ''touriste-routier'' was leading the Tour de France.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=100\u2013103}}\n\n==Changes from the previous Tour==\nIn 1931, the touriste-routiers started 10 minutes later than the national teams in some stages (2, 3, 4, 6, and 12).<ref name=\"mdc1931\"/>\nThe number of rest days in the Tour de France was reduced to three.<ref name=\"letour.fr\"/>\n\nThe time bonus for the winner, which had been used before in the [[1924 Tour de France]], was reintroduced.<ref name=\"mdc1931\"/>\n\n==Teams==\n{{main list|List of teams and cyclists in the 1931 Tour de France}}\nFor the second year, the race was run in the national team format, with six different teams. Belgium, Italy, Germany and France each sent a team with eight cyclists. Australia and Switzerland sent a combined team, each with four cyclists. The last team was the Spanish team, with only one cyclist. In addition, 40 cyclists joined as ''touriste-routiers''.<ref name=\"mdc1931\"/>\n\nThe French team was favourite, because they had dominated the 1930 Tour. The most competition was expected from the Belgian team, followed by the Italian team.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=100\u2013103}}\n\n==Race overview==\n{{main|1931 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 12|1931 Tour de France, Stage 13 to Stage 24}}\n[[File:Antonin Magne 1931 1.JPG|thumb|upright|[[Antonin Magne]], the winner of the 1931 Tour de France]]\nIn the early flat stages, the sprinters dominated.<ref name=\"letour.fr\"/> In the second stage, Austrian [[Max Bulla]] won the stage. He was a ''touriste-routier'', and had started ten minutes later than the A-class cyclists. He became the first, and only, touriste-routier to lead the Tour de France, and as of 2011 is the only Austrian to have led the race.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=100\u2013103}}<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/> Max Bulla was the only Austrian cyclist to win a stage in the Tour de France until [[2005 Tour de France|2005]], when [[Georg Totschnig]] won the 14th stage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://autobus.cyclingnews.com/road/2005/tour05/?id=/riders/2005/interviews/georg_totschnig_tour1405|title=An interview with Georg Totschnig, July 16, 2005 - His greatest sporting moment|publisher=Cyclingnews|date=16 July 2005|accessdate=30 September 2009}}</ref>\n\nAfter the fifth stage, [[Charles P\u00e9lissier]] and [[Rafaele di Paco]] shared the lead, thanks to the time bonus.<ref name=\"veloarchive\">{{cite web|url=http://www.veloarchive.com/races/tour/1931.php |title=1931: Magne makes his mark |author=Tom James |date=15 August 2003 |accessdate=30 September 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5kEXf41r6?url=http://www.veloarchive.com/races/tour/1931.php |archivedate=2 October 2009 |url-status=live }}</ref>\nAfter the seventh stage, the race was still completely open: the first 30 cyclists in the general classification were within 10 minutes of each other.<ref name=\"tdf.nl\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wielercentrum.com/tourdefrance/achtergronden%5Ctourverhalen%5C1931--Antonin-Magne-rijdt-zich-in-zijn-eerste-Tour-helemaal-leeg-513.html|title=1931: Antonin Magne rijdt zich in zijn eerste Tour helemaal leeg|publisher=Tourdefrance.nl|date=19 March 2003|language=Dutch|accessdate=30 September 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016215410/http://www.wielercentrum.com/tourdefrance/achtergronden/tourverhalen/1931--Antonin-Magne-rijdt-zich-in-zijn-eerste-Tour-helemaal-leeg-513.html|archive-date=16 October 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe defending champion, [[Andr\u00e9 Leducq]], was not in good shape. His teammate [[Antonin Magne]] took over the leading role in the French team.<ref name=\"revealed\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cyclingrevealed.com/timeline/Race%20Snippets/TdF/TdF1931.htm|author=Barry Boyce|year=2004|publisher=Cycling revealed|title=Two Victories in a Row for Team France|accessdate=30 September 2009}}</ref> In the first mountain stage, Belgian [[Jef Demuysere]] was away, with [[Antonin Magne]] trying to get him back. After a while, Jef Demuysere flatted, and at that moment Magne passed him. Magne had not seen Demuysere, and still thought he was chasing him.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp100\u2013103=}} He kept racing as fast as he could, and finished four minutes ahead of [[Antonio Pesenti]]. In the next stage, a large group finished together, and Magne was still leading the race with Pesenti as his closest competitor.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=100\u2013103}}\n\nIn the fourteenth stage, Pesenti was away with two teammates. The French team tried to get them back, but didn't succeed. In the end, Magne chased them by himself, but he could not get back to the Italians. His lead decreased to five minutes.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=100\u2013103}}\nIn the fifteenth stage, the Italians tried it again, but they were reeled back in by [[Charles P\u00e9lissier]]. Then [[Jef Demuysere]] got away, and won the stage with a margin of two minutes on Magne.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=100\u2013103}}\n\nBefore the penultimate stage, Magne was still leading the race, closely followed by Pesenti. Magne was not sure if he would win the race, because that stage would be over cobbles, on which the Belgian cyclists were considered experts. The night before the stage, Magne could not sleep, and his roommate Leducq suggested that he could read some fan mail. Magne considered reading fan mail before the race was over as giving bad luck, but one oversized letter made him curious.<ref name=\"revealed\"/> Magne opened it, and read a letter from a fan who claimed that Belgian cyclist [[Gaston Rebry]] (who had won the 1931 [[Paris\u2013Roubaix]] race over the same cobbles) had written to his mother that he was planning to attack on the penultimate stage, together with Jef Demuysere. Leducq thought the letter was a joke, but Magne did not take the risk and told his teammates to stay close to Rebry and Demuysere.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=100\u2013103}}\nAfter 60&nbsp;km, Rebry and Demuysere took off, and Magne followed them. The Belgians took turns to attack Magne, but they could not get away from him.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=100\u2013103}} They finished more than seventeen minutes ahead of Pesenti, which secured the victory for Magne and had Demuysere overtake Pesenti for the second place.<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Results==\n\nIn stages 2, 3, 4, 6, 7 and 12, the national teams started 10 minutes before the touriste-routiers; in all other stages all cyclists started together. The cyclist to reach the finish in the least time was the winner of the stage.\nThe time that each cyclist required to finish the stage was recorded. For the [[general classification in the Tour de France|general classification]], these times were added together. If a cyclist had received a time bonus, it was subtracted from this total; all time penalties were added to this total. The cyclist with the least accumulated time was the race leader, identified by the yellow jersey.\n\nThe team classification was calculated by adding up the times in the general classification of the three highest ranking cyclists per team; the team with the least time was the winner.\n\n===Stage winners===\n\nFive stages were won by touriste-routiers: Stages 2, 4, 7, 12 and 17, the highest number of stages ever won by touriste-routiers.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=100\u2013103}}\n[[File:Fabio Battesini.jpg|thumb|upright|alt=A man with a dirty face holding his bicycle, spare tires wrapped around his shoulders. In the background a large crowd.|[[Fabio Battesini]], the winner of the third stage]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Stage characteristics and winners<ref name=\"mdc1931\">{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1931.php |publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme |title=25\u00e8me Tour de France 1931 |language=French |accessdate=29 September 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306131219/http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1931.php |archivedate=6 March 2012 }}</ref>{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=29}}<ref name=\"topten\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cvccbike.com/tour/top_ten.html#1931 |title=Tour de France GC top ten |author=Arian Zwegers |publisher=CVCC |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5gWiBhPaH?url=http://www.cvccbike.com/tour/top_ten.html |archivedate=4 May 2009 |url-status=live |accessdate=20 April 2009 }}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Stage\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | Course\n! scope=\"col\" | Distance\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\" | Type<ref group=\"n\">There was no distinction in the rules between plain stages and mountain stages; the icons shown here indicate which stages included mountains.</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" | Winner\n! scope=\"col\" | Race leader\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1931 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 12#Stage 1|1]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |30 June|| [[Paris]] to [[Caen]] ||{{convert|208|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Alfred Haemerlinck]]|BEL}} || {{flagathlete|[[Alfred Haemerlinck]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1931 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 12#Stage 2|2]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |1 July|| [[Caen]] to [[Dinan]] ||{{convert|212|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Max Bulla]]|AUT}} || {{flagathlete|[[Max Bulla]]|AUT}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1931 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 12#Stage 3|3]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2 July|| [[Dinan]] to [[Brest, France|Brest]] ||{{convert|206|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Fabio Battesini]]|ITA|1861}} || {{flagathlete|[[L\u00e9on Le Calvez]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1931 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 12#Stage 4|4]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |3 July|| [[Brest, France|Brest]] to [[Vannes]] ||{{convert|211|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Andr\u00e9 Godinat]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Rafaele di Paco]]|ITA|1861}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1931 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 12#Stage 5|5]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |4 July|| [[Vannes]] to [[Les Sables d'Olonne]] ||{{convert|202|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Charles P\u00e9lissier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Charles P\u00e9lissier]]|FRA}}<br/>{{flagathlete|[[Rafaele di Paco]]|ITA|1861}}<ref group=\"n\">After the 5th stage, P\u00e9lissier and di Paco had the same time in the general classification. There was no rule for this, so both received the yellow jersey.</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1931 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 12#Stage 6|6]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |5 July|| [[Les Sables d'Olonne]] to [[Bordeaux]] ||{{convert|338|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Alfred Haemerlinck]]|BEL}} || {{flagathlete|[[Rafaele di Paco]]|ITA|1861}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1931 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 12#Stage 7|7]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |6 July|| [[Bordeaux]] to [[Bayonne]] ||{{convert|180|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[G\u00e9rard Loncke]]|BEL}} || {{flagathlete|[[Rafaele di Paco]]|ITA|1861}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1931 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 12#Stage 8|8]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |7 July|| [[Bayonne]] to [[Pau, Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques|Pau]] ||{{convert|106|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Charles P\u00e9lissier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Charles P\u00e9lissier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1931 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 12#Stage 9|9]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |8 July|| [[Pau, Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques|Pau]] to [[Luchon]] || style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|231|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) || {{flagathlete|[[Antonin Magne]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Antonin Magne]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1931 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 12#Stage 10|10]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |10 July|| [[Luchon]] to [[Perpignan]] || style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|322|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) || {{flagathlete|[[Rafaele di Paco]]|ITA|1861}} || {{flagathlete|[[Antonin Magne]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1931 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 12#Stage 11|11]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |12 July|| [[Perpignan]] to [[Montpellier]] ||{{convert|164|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Rafaele di Paco]]|ITA|1861}} || {{flagathlete|[[Antonin Magne]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1931 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 12#Stage 12|12]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |13 July|| [[Montpellier]] to [[Marseille]] ||{{convert|207|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Max Bulla]]|AUT}} || {{flagathlete|[[Antonin Magne]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1931 Tour de France, Stage 13 to Stage 24#Stage 13|13]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |14 July|| [[Marseille]] to [[Cannes]] ||{{convert|181|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Charles P\u00e9lissier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Antonin Magne]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1931 Tour de France, Stage 13 to Stage 24#Stage 14|14]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |15 July|| [[Cannes]] to [[Nice, France|Nice]] || style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|132|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) || {{flagathlete|[[Eugenio Gestri]]|ITA|1861}} || {{flagathlete|[[Antonin Magne]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1931 Tour de France, Stage 13 to Stage 24#Stage 15|15]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |17 July|| [[Nice]] to [[Gap, Hautes-Alpes|Gap]] || style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|233|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) || {{flagathlete|[[Jef Demuysere]]|BEL}} || {{flagathlete|[[Antonin Magne]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1931 Tour de France, Stage 13 to Stage 24#Stage 16|16]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |18 July|| [[Gap, Hautes-Alpes|Gap]] to [[Grenoble]] || style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|102|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) || {{flagathlete|[[Charles P\u00e9lissier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Antonin Magne]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1931 Tour de France, Stage 13 to Stage 24#Stage 17|17]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |19 July|| [[Grenoble]] to [[Aix-les-Bains]] || style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|230|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) || {{flagathlete|[[Max Bulla]]|AUT}} || {{flagathlete|[[Antonin Magne]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1931 Tour de France, Stage 13 to Stage 24#Stage 18|18]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |20 July|| [[Aix-les-Bains]] to [[\u00c9vian-les-Bains|Evian]] || style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|204|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) || {{flagathlete|[[Jef Demuysere]]|BEL}} || {{flagathlete|[[Antonin Magne]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1931 Tour de France, Stage 13 to Stage 24#Stage 19|19]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |21 July|| [[Evian]] to [[Belfort]] || style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|282|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) || {{flagathlete|[[Rafaele di Paco]]|ITA|1861}} || {{flagathlete|[[Antonin Magne]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1931 Tour de France, Stage 13 to Stage 24#Stage 20|20]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |22 July|| [[Belfort]] to [[Colmar]] || style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|209|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) || {{flagathlete|[[Andr\u00e9 Leducq]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Antonin Magne]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1931 Tour de France, Stage 13 to Stage 24#Stage 21|21]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |23 July|| [[Colmar]] to [[Metz]] ||{{convert|192|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Rafaele di Paco]]|ITA|1861}} || {{flagathlete|[[Antonin Magne]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1931 Tour de France, Stage 13 to Stage 24#Stage 22|22]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |24 July|| [[Metz]] to [[Charleville-M\u00e9zi\u00e8res|Charleville]] ||{{convert|159|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Raffaele di Paco]]|ITA|1861}} || {{flagathlete|[[Antonin Magne]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1931 Tour de France, Stage 13 to Stage 24#Stage 23|23]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|25 July|| [[Charleville-M\u00e9zi\u00e8res|Charleville]] to [[Malo-les-Bains]] ||{{convert|271|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Gaston Rebry]]|BEL}} || {{flagathlete|[[Antonin Magne]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1931 Tour de France, Stage 13 to Stage 24#Stage 24|24]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |26 July|| [[Malo-les-Bains]] to [[Paris]] ||{{convert|313|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Charles P\u00e9lissier]]|FRA}} || {{flagathlete|[[Antonin Magne]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| Total\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"text-align:center\"| {{convert|5091|km|0|abbr=on}}{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=108}}\n|}\n{{reflist|group=\"Stage notes\"}}\n\n===General classification===\n\n[[File:Louis Peglion.jpg|thumb|upright|alt=A man holding flowers|[[Louis Peglion]], seventh place in the general classification]]\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:38em;margin-bottom:0;\"\n|+ Final general classification (1\u201310)<ref name=\"mdc1931\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Rank!! scope=\"col\" | Rider!! scope=\"col\" | Team!! scope=\"col\" | Time\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |1\n| {{flagathlete|[[Antonin Magne]]|FRA}} || France || style=\"text-align:right;\" | 177h 10' 03\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |2\n| {{flagathlete|[[Jef Demuysere]]|BEL}} || Belgium|| style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 12' 56\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |3\n| {{flagathlete|[[Antonio Pesenti]]|ITA|1861}}||Italy|| style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 22' 51\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |4\n| {{flagathlete|[[Gaston Rebry]]|BEL}} || Belgium|| style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 46' 40\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |5\n| {{flagathlete|[[Maurice De Waele]]|BEL}} || Belgium|| style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 49' 46\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |6\n| {{flagathlete|[[Julien Vervaecke]]|BEL}} || Belgium|| style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 1h 10' 11\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |7\n| {{flagathlete|[[Louis Peglion]]|FRA}} || France || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 1h 18' 33\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |8\n| {{flagathlete|[[Erich Metze]]|GER|Weimar}} ||Germany|| style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 1h 20' 59\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |9\n| {{flagathlete|[[Albert B\u00fcchi]]|SUI}} ||Australia/Switzerland|| style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 1h 29' 29\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |10\n| {{flagathlete|[[Andr\u00e9 Leducq]]|FRA}} || France || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 1h 30' 08\"\n|}\n{| class=\"collapsible collapsed wikitable\" style=\"width:38em;margin-top:-1px;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"4\" | Final general classification (11\u201335)\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Rank!! scope=\"col\" | Rider!! scope=\"col\" | Team!! scope=\"col\" | Time\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | 11\n| {{flagathlete|[[Oskar Thierbach]]|GER|Weimar}}|| Germany || style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 1h 34' 