://www.metacritic.com/game/xbox-360/nhl-08 |title=NHL 08 for Xbox 360 Reviews |website=Metacritic |accessdate=June 28, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n\n== Legacy ==\nNHL 08 was included in [[EA Sports 08 Collection]] in 2008 along with [[Madden NFL 08]], [[Tiger Woods PGA Tour 08]], [[FIFA 08]] and [[NBA Live 08]].<ref>{{cite web |last= |first= |date= |url=https://www.gamespot.com/ea-sports-08-collection |title=EA Sports 08 Collection |website=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=January 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{moby game|id=/nhl-08}}\n\n{{NHL series}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nhl 08}}\n[[Category:2007 video games]]\n[[Category:Electronic Arts games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 2 games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 3 games]]\n[[Category:Xbox 360 games]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:NHL (video game series)]]\n[[Category:EA Sports games]]\n[[Category:Video games set in 2007]]\n[[Category:Video games set in 2008]]\n[[Category:Video games set in the United States]]\n[[Category:Video games set in Canada]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Canada]]\n", "name_user": "Lacon432", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLegacy", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NHL_08"}
{"title_page": "1930 Tour de France", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox cycling race report\n| name        = 1930 Tour de France\n| image       = Tour de France 1930.png\n| image_caption   = Route of the 1930 Tour de France followed counterclockwise, starting in Paris\n| image_alt     = \n| image_size         = 300px\n| date        = 2\u201327 July\n| stages       = 21\n| distance      = 4822\n| unit        = km\n| time        = 186h 39' 16\"\n| first       = [[Andr\u00e9 Leducq]]\n| first_nat     = FRA\n| first_color    = yellow\n| first_team     = France\n| second       = [[Learco Guerra]]\n| second_nat     = ITA\n| second_natvar   = 1861\n| second_team    = Italy\n| third       = [[Antonin Magne]]\n| third_nat     = FRA\n| third_team     = France\n| team        = France\n| previous      = [[1929 Tour de France|1929]]\n| next        = [[1931 Tour de France|1931]]\n}}\nThe '''1930 Tour de France''' was the 24th edition of the [[Tour de France]], taking place from 2 to 27 July. It consisted of 21 stages over {{convert|4822|km|0|abbr=on}}.\n\nThe 24th tour de France introduced a new format to team racing; teams were organised by country with ten riders per team. This format proved to be a very successful format for the French riders, six of which placed in the top ten. Andr\u00e9 Leducq was the star of the French team, winning the overall classification, however, Charles P\u00e9lissier, who finished ninth overall achieved a stunning eight stage wins.<ref name=\"letour.fr\">{{cite web|url=http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/1930/histoire.html|title=The Tour - Year 1930|publisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|accessdate=30 September 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090716154747/http://www.letour.fr/HISTO/us/TDF/1930/histoire.html|archive-date=16 July 2009|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n1930 was the first year of the publicity caravan.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.letour.fr/2008/TDF/COURSE/us/histoire_home.html |title=Le Tour (official site), History, 1930 |access-date=27 July 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080615022439/http://www.letour.fr/2008/TDF/COURSE/us/histoire_home.html |archive-date=15 June 2008 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Changes from the previous Tour==\nTour director [[Henri Desgrange]] had tried many things to remove the team tactics from the Tour de France, because he wanted the race to be won on individual strength. In 1929, he had removed the sponsors, but this had had no effect; the Alcyon team members still cooperated and managed to let [[Maurice Dewaele]] win the race, even though he was sick.\nFor 1930, Desgrange replaced the trade teams by national teams. He gave up on the idea that he could keep team tactics away from the Tour, but decided that he could still try to keep commercial team tactics away.<ref name=\"veloarchive\">{{cite web|url=http://www.veloarchive.com/races/tour/1930.php|title=1930: The coming of national teams|author=Tom James|date=15 August 2003|accessdate=29 September 2009}}</ref>\nThe race started with five national teams of eight cyclists each, completed by 60 touriste-routiers.<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/><ref name=\"mdc1930\"/> All cyclists raced on identical, yellow-coloured bicycles.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=94\u2013100}}\n\nThe trade teams did not like the national teams, because they lost the publicity during the most important race of the season, while they still had to pay for the riders' salary. The trade teams used to supply food, transport and lodging for the cyclists during the race, but now the Tour organisation had to pay for all this. To pay for this, the publicity caravan was started.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=94\u2013100}} In 1930, only three companies were in that publicity caravan, but it has grown since.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=94\u2013100}} The most popular sponsor in the publicity was Menier chocolates, whose advertising manager had advised the Tour organisation to start the publicity caravan; 500.000 fans came to the Tour de France stages early to receive chocolate handouts.<ref name=\"revealed\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cyclingrevealed.com/timeline/Race%20Snippets/TdF/TdF1930.htm|publisher=Cycling revealed|author=Barry Boyce|year=2004|title=New ideas! Bold Initiatives!|accessdate=30 September 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 1929, all cyclists had to do their own repairs, and had to finish with their bicycle they started with. This had caused [[Victor Fontan]] to quit the race while he was leading. In 1930, this rule was abandoned, and from now on, cyclists could get help when they had mechanical problems.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=94\u2013100}}\n\nFrom 1927 to 1929, some stages were run in the team-time-trial format. This was completely abandoned in 1930.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=94\u2013100}}\n\nThe first live radio broadcast from the Tour de France happened in 1930.<ref name=\"letour.fr\"/>\n\nTwo extra prizes were given in 1930, donated by the Soors brothers from ''Grand Sport''. The cyclist who led the general classification, and therefore wore the yellow jersey, received the ''Maillot d'or'' (French for ''golden jersey''), which was 1000 francs for every stage. The best touriste-routier in the general classification received the ''Maillot d'argent'' (French for ''silver jersey''), which was 500 francs per stage. Despite the name, there was no silver jersey worn by the best touriste-routier.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cyclismag.com/article.php?sid=1223|title=Le myst\u00e8re du maillot argent r\u00e9solu|date=5 July 2005|accessdate=18 July 2013|language=French|publisher=Cyclismag|first=Sandrine|last=Viollet|author2=Turgis, Dominique|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708215419/http://www.cyclismag.com/article.php?sid=1223|archive-date=8 July 2011|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref>\n\n==Teams==\n{{main list|List of teams and cyclists in the 1930 Tour de France}}\n\nFor the first time, the Tour was run with national teams. Belgium, Italy, Spain, Germany and France each sent a team composed of eight cyclists. Additionally, 60 cyclists started as ''touriste-routiers'', most of them French. Some of them were grouped in regional teams.<ref name=\"mdc1930\"/>\n\nOne of the notable cyclists was [[Alfredo Binda]], riding in the Italian national team. He had dominated the [[Giro d'Italia]] in the recent years, winning the [[1925 Giro d'Italia|1925]], [[1927 Giro d'Italia|1927]], [[1928 Giro d'Italia|1928]] and [[1929 Giro d'Italia|1929]] editions; in 1929 he had done so by winning eight consecutive stages. For the [[1930 Giro d'Italia]], he was paid money not to compete, so he started in the Tour de France that year.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=94\u2013100}}\nThe French team was captained by [[Victor Fontan]], who had been leading the [[1929 Tour de France]] until he had to abandon the race due to mechanical problems. The Belgian team had [[Jef Demuysere]] as the favourite.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wielercentrum.com/tourdefrance/achtergronden%5Ctourverhalen%5C1930--Andr%C3%A9-Leducq-wint-de-eerste-Tour-voor-landenploegen-512.html|title=1930: Andr\u00e9 Leducq wint de eerste Tour voor landenploegen|publisher=Tourdefrance.nl|language=Dutch|date=19 March 2003|accessdate=30 September 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016215117/http://www.wielercentrum.com/tourdefrance/achtergronden/tourverhalen/1930--Andr%C3%A9-Leducq-wint-de-eerste-Tour-voor-landenploegen-512.html|archive-date=16 October 2012|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref>\n\n==Route and stages==\n\nThe [[List of highest points reached in the Tour de France|highest point of elevation in the race]] was {{convert|2556|m|ft|abbr=on}} at the summit tunnel of the [[Col du Galibier]] mountain pass on stage 16.{{sfn|Augendre|2016|pp=177\u2013178}}<ref>{{cite news|title=Cinq \u00e9quipes nationales de huit coureurs et soixante touristes routies commenceront, demain mercredi, le 24e Tour de France|trans-title=Five national teams of eight riders and sixty touring tourists will start the 24th Tour de France tomorrow Wednesday|url=https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k9796262n/f2.item|work=[[:fr:Le Miroir des sports|Le Miroir des sports]]|date=1 July 1930|page=2|language=French|via=[[Gallica]]e}}</ref>\n\n[[Charles P\u00e9lissier]] won four stages in a row. He was the last cyclist to do this, until [[Mario Cipollini]] repeated this in [[1999 Tour de France|1999]].<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/> P\u00e9lissier had also crossed the line first in the sixth stage, but was relegated because he had pulled Binda's jersey.<ref name=\"mdc1930\"/> He also finished in second place seven times, and finished in the top-three eighteen out of 21 times.<ref name=\"letour.fr\"/>\n\nP\u00e9lissier was dominating the flat stages, but lost time on the mountain stages. In stage 9, he finished in fifteenth place, losing more than 23 minutes,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1930_9.php|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306131248/http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1930_9.php|archive-date=6 March 2012|access-date=28 October 2016|url-status=dead|publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme|title=24\u00e8me Tour de France 1930 - 9\u00e8me \u00e9tape|language=French}}</ref> in stage 14 he lost another 75 seconds to Leducq,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1930_14.php|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306131253/http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1930_14.php|archive-date=6 March 2012|access-date=28 October 2016|url-status=dead|publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme|title=24\u00e8me Tour de France 1930 - 14\u00e8me \u00e9tape|language=French}}</ref> and in stage 15 he lost more than 50 minutes, finishing 31st.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1930_15.php|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306131307/http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1930_15.php|archive-date=6 March 2012|access-date=28 October 2016|url-status=dead|publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme|title=24\u00e8me Tour de France 1930 - 15\u00e8me \u00e9tape|language=French}}</ref> P\u00e9lissier's eight stage victories in one Tour is still a record; it has since been equalled by [[Eddy Merckx]] in [[1970 Tour de France|1970]] and [[1974 Tour de France|1974]], and [[Freddy Maertens]] in [[1976 Tour de France|1976]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Henrys|first=Colin|title=Who has won the most Tour de France stages?|url=https://roadcyclinguk.com/racing/won-tour-de-france-stages.html|access-date=6 September 2016|work=Road Cycling UK|publisher=Mpora|date=5 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Stage characteristics and winners<ref name=\"mdc1930\">{{cite web|url=http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1930.php|publisher=M\u00e9moire du cyclisme|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306131211/http://memoire-du-cyclisme.net/eta_tdf_1903_1939/tdf1930.php|archive-date=6 March 2012|access-date=28 October 2016|url-status=dead|title=24\u00e8me Tour de France 1930|language=French}}</ref>{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=28}}<ref name=\"topten\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cvccbike.com/tour/top_ten.html#1912 |title=Tour de France GC top ten |author=Arian Zwegers |publisher=CVCC |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/5gWiBhPaH?url=http://www.cvccbike.com/tour/top_ten.html |archive-date=4 May 2009 |url-status=live |accessdate=20 April 2009 |df= }}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Stage\n! scope=\"col\" | Date\n! scope=\"col\" | Course\n! scope=\"col\" | Distance\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\" | Type<ref group=\"n\">In 1930, there was no distinction in the rules between plain stages and mountain stages; the icons shown here indicate whether the stage included mountains.</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" | Winner\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 1|1]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |2 July|| [[Paris]] to [[Caen]] ||{{convert|206|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Charles P\u00e9lissier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 2|2]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |3 July|| [[Caen]] to [[Dinan]] ||{{convert|203|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Learco Guerra]]|ITA|1861}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 3|3]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |4 July|| [[Dinan]] to [[Brest, France|Brest]] ||{{convert|206|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Charles P\u00e9lissier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 4|4]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |5 July|| [[Brest, France|Brest]] to [[Vannes]] ||{{convert|210|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Omer Taverne]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 5|5]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |6 July|| [[Vannes]] to [[Les Sables d'Olonne]] ||{{convert|202|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Andr\u00e9 Leducq]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 6|6]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |7 July|| [[Les Sables d'Olonne]] to [[Bordeaux]] ||{{convert|285|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Jean Aerts]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 7|7]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |8 July|| [[Bordeaux]] to [[Hendaye]] ||{{convert|222|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Jules Merviel]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 8|8]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |9 July|| [[Hendaye]] to [[Pau, Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques|Pau]] ||{{convert|146|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Alfredo Binda]]|ITA|1861}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 9|9]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |10 July|| [[Pau, Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques|Pau]] to [[Luchon]] || style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|231|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) || {{flagathlete|[[Alfredo Binda]]|ITA|1861}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 10|10]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |12 July|| [[Luchon]] to [[Perpignan]] || style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|322|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) || {{flagathlete|[[Charles P\u00e9lissier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 11|11]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |14 July|| [[Perpignan]] to [[Montpellier]] ||{{convert|164|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Charles P\u00e9lissier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 12|12]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |15 July|| [[Montpellier]] to [[Marseille]] ||{{convert|209|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Antonin Magne]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 13|13]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |16 July|| [[Marseille]] to [[Cannes]] ||{{convert|181|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Learco Guerra]]|ITA|1861}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 14|14]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |17 July|| [[Cannes]] to [[Nice]] || style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|132|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) || {{flagathlete|[[Louis Peglion]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 15|15]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |19 July|| [[Nice]] to [[Grenoble]] || style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|333|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) || {{flagathlete|[[Learco Guerra]]|ITA|1861}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 16|16]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |21 July|| [[Grenoble]] to [[\u00c9vian-les-Bains|Evian]] || style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|331|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) || {{flagathlete|[[Andr\u00e9 Leducq]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 17|17]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |23 July|| [[Evian]] to [[Belfort]] || style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|282|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) || {{flagathlete|[[Frans Bonduel]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 18|18]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |24 July|| [[Belfort]] to [[Metz]] ||{{convert|223|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Charles P\u00e9lissier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 19|19]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |25 July|| [[Metz]] to [[Charleville-M\u00e9zi\u00e8res|Charleville]] ||{{convert|159|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Charles P\u00e9lissier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 20|20]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |26 July|| [[Charleville-M\u00e9zi\u00e8res|Charleville]] to [[Malo-les-Bains]] ||{{convert|271|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Charles P\u00e9lissier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 21|21]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |27 July|| [[Malo-les-Bains]] to [[Paris]] ||{{convert|300|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Charles P\u00e9lissier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| Total\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center\"| {{convert|4822|km|0|abbr=on}}{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=108}}\n|}\n\n==Race overview==\n{{main|1930 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 11|1930 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21}}\n[[File:Onderhoud tijdens rustdag - Taking care of the bicycles during a rest day.jpg|thumb|right|Taking care of / maintenance of the racing bicycles during a rest day in Belfort.|alt=Some persons looking at and doing things to bicycles.]]\nIn the first stage, [[Charles P\u00e9lissier]] won, and he became leader of the race, the third of the P\u00e9lissier brothers to do so.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=94\u2013100}} In the first stages, before the Pyrenees, the sprinters were battling for stage victories. The Italian [[Learco Guerra]] dominated the race. For the general classification, no big things happened, except for the fall of [[Alfredo Binda]] in the seventh stage, which caused him to lose one hour, and abandon his hopes for the Tour victory.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=94\u2013100}} Binda won the eighth and ninth stage, before he dropped out in the tenth stage.<ref name=\"revealed\"/>\nIn the ninth stage, touriste-routier [[Beno\u00eet Faur\u00e9]] led the race over the first mountains, and dropped many cyclists. In the end, he was dropped by Binda, Leducq, Pierre Magne and Antonin Magne.\n\nIn the sixteenth stage, going down from the [[Col du Galibier|Galibier]], the leader of the race [[Andr\u00e9 Leducq]] fell down.<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/> He lost consciousness, and when he woke up, [[Pierre Magne (cyclist)|Pierre Magne]] put him back on his bicycle, and his French teammates helped him to get back. [[Learco Guerra]], second placed in the general classification with a margin of more than 16 minutes, saw an opportunity and was away as fast as he could, together with [[Jef Demuysere]]. Just before the climb of the [[Col du T\u00e9l\u00e9graphe]], Leducq's pedal broke. His teammate [[Marcel Bidot]] got a pedal from a spectator's bicycle. Leducq thought of abandoning the race, but he was convinced by his teammates to get back on his bicycle. They had 60&nbsp;km to go, and managed to get back to Guerra. In the end, Leducq even managed to win the sprint.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=94\u2013100}}\n\nWith no more mountain stages to come, Leducq had secured his victory. Charles P\u00e9lissier made the victory of the French team even more glorious, as he won the last four stages.\n\n==Classification leadership and minor prizes==\nIn all stages, all cyclists started together. The cyclist to reach the finish first was the winner of the stage.\nThe time that each cyclist required to finish the stage was recorded. For the [[general classification in the Tour de France|general classification]], these times were added together; the cyclist with the least accumulated time was the race leader, identified by the yellow jersey.\n\nThe touriste-routiers had been divided into regional teams, for which a separate team classification was made. The South-East team became the winner of this classification.<ref name=\"mdc1930\"/> For ''touriste-routiers'', cyclists that were not part of national teams, there were additional awards. The best-placed touriste-routier received a prize, but was not identified by a jersey. Some of the touriste-routiers were assigned to a regional team. A regional team classification was also made, according to the same rules as the national team classification.\n\nThe organing newspaper, [[l'Auto]] named a ''meilleur grimpeur'' (best climber), an unofficial precursor to the modern [[King of the Mountains]] competition. This award was won by [[Beno\u00eet Faur\u00e9]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tour-giro-vuelta.net|title=Tour-giro-vuelta|accessdate=29 September 2009|author=Michiel van Lonkhuyzen}}</ref>\n\nFor the first time, there was a [[Team classification in the Tour de France|team competition]]. The team classification was calculated in 1930 by adding up the times in the general classification of the three highest ranking cyclists per national team; the national team with the least time was the winner. The team competition for national teams was won by the French team.<ref name=\"mdc1930\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:smaller; clear:both;\"\n|+Classification leadership by stage<ref name=\"tdf-statistics\">{{cite web|last=van den Akker|first=Pieter|title=Informatie over de Tour de France van 1930|trans-title=Information about the Tour de France from 1930|url=http://www.tourdefrancestatistieken.nl/tour.php?jaar=1930|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190304022401/http://www.tourdefrancestatistieken.nl/tour.php?jaar=1930|archive-date=4 March 2019|language=Dutch|website=TourDeFranceStatistieken.nl|accessdate=4 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n! style=\"width:1%;\"| Stage\n! style=\"width:19%;\"| Winner\n! style=\"width:19%;\"| [[General classification]]\n! style=\"width:19%;\"| Best touriste-routier\n! style=\"width:19%;\"| [[Team classification in the Tour de France|National classification]]\n! style=\"width:19%;\"| Regional classification\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 1|1]]\n| [[Charles P\u00e9lissier]]\n|style=\"background:#FFEB64;\"| [[Charles P\u00e9lissier]]\n|style=\"background:lightgrey;\" rowspan=6| Several cyclists<br/>with the same time\n| style=\"background:lightblue;\"| France\n| style=\"background:#ffc;\" rowspan=\"6\"| North-France\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 2|2]]\n| [[Learco Guerra]]\n|style=\"background:#FFEB64;\" rowspan=7| [[Learco Guerra]]\n|style=\"background:lightblue;\" rowspan=2| Italy\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 3|3]]\n| [[Charles P\u00e9lissier]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 4|4]]\n| [[Omer Taverne]]\n|style=\"background:lightblue;\" rowspan=18| France\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 5|5]]\n| [[Andr\u00e9 Leducq]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 6|6]]\n| [[Jean Aerts]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 7|7]]\n| [[Jules Merviel]]\n|style=\"background:lightgrey;\" rowspan=2| [[Jean Gouleme]]\n| style=\"background:#ffc;\" rowspan=\"15\"| South-East France\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 8|8]]\n| [[Alfredo Binda]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 9|9]]\n| [[Alfredo Binda]]\n|style=\"background:#FFEB64;\" rowspan=13| [[Andr\u00e9 Leducq]]\n|style=\"background:lightgrey;\" rowspan=13| [[Beno\u00eet Faure]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 10|10]]\n| [[Charles P\u00e9lissier]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 11|11]]\n| [[Charles P\u00e9lissier]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 12|12]]\n| [[Antonin Magne]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 13|13]]\n| [[Learco Guerra]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 14|14]]\n| [[Louis Peglion]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 15|15]]\n| [[Learco Guerra]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 16|16]]\n| [[Andr\u00e9 Leducq]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 17|17]]\n| [[Frans Bonduel]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 18|18]]\n| [[Charles P\u00e9lissier]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 19|19]]\n| [[Charles P\u00e9lissier]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 20|20]]\n| [[Charles P\u00e9lissier]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 21|21]]\n| [[Charles P\u00e9lissier]]\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | Final\n! style=\"background:#FFDB00;\"| [[Andr\u00e9 Leducq]]\n! style=\"background:silver;\"| [[Beno\u00eet Faure]]\n! style=\"background:#82CAFA;\"| France\n! style=\"background:#FFF380;\"| South-East France\n|}\n\n==Final standings==\n\n===General classification===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:43em;margin-bottom:0;\"\n|+ Final general classification (1\u201310)<ref name=\"mdc1930\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Rank!! scope=\"col\" | Rider!! scope=\"col\" | Team!! scope=\"col\" | Time\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |1\n| {{flagathlete|[[Andr\u00e9 Leducq]]|FRA}} ||France|| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 172h 12' 16\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |2\n| {{flagathlete|[[Learco Guerra]]|ITA|1861}}||Italy|| style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 14' 13\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |3\n| {{flagathlete|[[Antonin Magne]]|FRA}} ||France|| style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 16' 03\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |4\n| {{flagathlete|[[Jef Demuysere]]|BEL}} ||Belgium|| style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 21' 34\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |5\n| {{flagathlete|[[Marcel Bidot]]|FRA}} ||France|| style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 41' 18\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |6\n| {{flagathlete|[[Pierre Magne (cyclist)|Pierre Magne]]|FRA}} ||France|| style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 45' 42\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |7\n| {{flagathlete|[[Frans Bonduel]]|BEL}} ||Belgium|| style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 56' 19\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |8\n| {{flagathlete|[[Beno\u00eet Faur\u00e9]]|FRA}} ||Touriste-routier (South-East)|| style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 58' 34\"\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |9\n| {{flagathlete|[[Charles P\u00e9lissier]]|FRA}} ||France|| style=\"text-align:right;\" | + 1h 04' 37\"\n|-\