style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|331|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) || {{flagathlete|[[Andr\u00e9 Leducq]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 17|17]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |23 July|| [[Evian]] to [[Belfort]] || style=\"text-align:center;\" | {{convert|282|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Mountainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Stage with mountain(s) || {{flagathlete|[[Frans Bonduel]]|BEL}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 18|18]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |24 July|| [[Belfort]] to [[Metz]] ||{{convert|223|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Charles P\u00e9lissier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 19|19]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |25 July|| [[Metz]] to [[Charleville-M\u00e9zi\u00e8res|Charleville]] ||{{convert|159|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Charles P\u00e9lissier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 20|20]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |26 July|| [[Charleville-M\u00e9zi\u00e8res|Charleville]] to [[Malo-les-Bains]] ||{{convert|271|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Charles P\u00e9lissier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21#Stage 21|21]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" |27 July|| [[Malo-les-Bains]] to [[Paris]] ||{{convert|300|km|mi|abbr=on}} || [[File:Plainstage.svg|20px|alt=|link=]] || Plain stage || {{flagathlete|[[Charles P\u00e9lissier]]|FRA}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| Total\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center\"| {{convert|4822|km|0|abbr=on}}{{sfn|Augendre|2016|p=108}}\n|}\n\n==Race overview==\n{{main|1930 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 11|1930 Tour de France, Stage 12 to Stage 21}}\n[[File:Onderhoud tijdens rustdag - Taking care of the bicycles during a rest day.jpg|thumb|right|Taking care of / maintenance of the racing bicycles during a rest day in Belfort.|alt=Some persons looking at and doing things to bicycles.]]\nIn the first stage, [[Charles P\u00e9lissier]] won, and he became leader of the race, the third of the P\u00e9lissier brothers to do so.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=94\u2013100}} In the first stages, before the Pyrenees, the sprinters were battling for stage victories. The Italian [[Learco Guerra]] dominated the race. For the general classification, no big things happened, except for the fall of [[Alfredo Binda]] in the seventh stage, which caused him to lose one hour, and abandon his hopes for the Tour victory.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=94\u2013100}} Binda won the eighth and ninth stage, before he dropped out in the tenth stage.<ref name=\"revealed\"/>\nIn the ninth stage, touriste-routier [[Beno\u00eet Faur\u00e9]] led the race over the first mountains, and dropped many cyclists. In the end, he was dropped by Binda, Leducq, Pierre Magne and Antonin Magne.\n\nIn the sixteenth stage, going down from the [[Col du Galibier|Galibier]], the leader of the race [[Andr\u00e9 Leducq]] fell down.<ref name=\"veloarchive\"/> He lost consciousness, and when he woke up, [[Pierre Magne (cyclist)|Pierre Magne]] put him back on his bicycle, and his French teammates helped him to get back. [[Learco Guerra]], second placed in the general classification with a margin of more than 16 minutes, saw an opportunity and was away as fast as he could, together with [[Jef Demuysere]]. Just before the climb of the [[Col du T\u00e9l\u00e9graphe]], Leducq's pedal broke. His teammate [[Marcel Bidot]] got a pedal from a spectator's bicycle. Leducq thought of abandoning the race, but he was convinced by his teammates to get back on his bicycle. They had 60&nbsp;km to go, and managed to get back to Guerra. In the end, Leducq even managed to win the sprint.{{sfn|McGann|McGann|2006|pp=94\u2013100}}\n\nWith no more mountain stages to come, Leducq had secured his victory. Charles P\u00e9lissier made the victory of the French team even more glorious, as he won the last four stages.\n\n==Classification leadership and minor prizes==\nIn all stages, all cyclists started together. The cyclist to reach the finish first was the winner of the stage.\nThe time that each cyclist required to finish the stage was recorded. For the [[general classification in the Tour de France|general classification]], these times were added together; the cyclist with the least accumulated time was the race leader, identified by the yellow jersey.\n\nThe touriste-routiers had been divided into regional teams, for which a separate team classification was made. The South-East team became the winner of this classification.<ref name=\"mdc1930\"/> For ''touriste-routiers'', cyclists that were not part of national teams, there were additional awards. The best-placed touriste-routier received a prize, but was not identified by a jersey. Some of the touriste-routiers were assigned to a regional team. A regional team classification was also made, according to the same rules as the national team classification.\n\nThe organing newspaper, [[l'Auto]] named a ''meilleur grimpeur'' (best climber), an unofficial precursor to the modern [[King of the Mountains]] competition. This award was won by [[Beno\u00eet Faur\u00e9]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tour-giro-vuelta.net|title=Tour-giro-vuelta|accessdate=29 September 2009|author=Michiel van Lonkhuyzen}}</ref>\n\nFor the first time, there was a [[Team classification in the Tour de France|team competition]]. The team classification was calculated in 1930 by adding up the times in the general classification of the three highest ranking cyclists per national team; the national team with the least time was the winner. The team competition for national teams was won by the French team.<ref name=\"mdc1930\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:smaller; clear:both;\"\n|+Classification leadership by stage<ref name=\"tdf-statistics\">{{cite web|last=van den Akker|first=Pieter|title=Informatie over de Tour de France van 1930|trans-title=Information about the Tour de France from 1930|url=http://www.tourdefrancestatistieken.nl/tour.php?jaar=1930|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190304022401/http://www.tourdefrancestatistieken.nl/tour.php?jaar=1930|archive-date=4 March 2019|language=Dutch|website=TourDeFranceStatistieken.nl|accessdate=4 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n! style=\"width:1%;\"| Stage\n! style=\"width:19%;\"| Winner\n! style=\"width:19%;\"| [[General classification]]\n! style=\"width:19%;\"| Best touriste-routier\n! style=\"width:19%;\"| [[Team classification in the Tour de France|National classification]]\n! style=\"width:19%;\"| Regional classification\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 1|1]]\n| [[Charles P\u00e9lissier]]\n|style=\"background:#FFEB64;\"| [[Charles P\u00e9lissier]]\n|style=\"background:lightgrey;\" rowspan=6| Several cyclists<br/>with the same time\n| style=\"background:lightblue;\"| France\n| style=\"background:#ffc;\" rowspan=\"6\"| North-France\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 2|2]]\n| [[Learco Guerra]]\n|style=\"background:#FFEB64;\" rowspan=7| [[Learco Guerra]]\n|style=\"background:lightblue;\" rowspan=2| Italy\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 3|3]]\n| [[Charles P\u00e9lissier]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 4|4]]\n| [[Omer Taverne]]\n|style=\"background:lightblue;\" rowspan=18| France\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 5|5]]\n| [[Andr\u00e9 Leducq]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de France, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 6|6]]\n| [[Jean Aerts]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | [[1930 Tour de Fran