lisher=[[Amaury Sport Organisation]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817121602/http://netstorage.lequipe.fr/ASO/cyclisme/le-tour/2016/histoire/TDF16_GH_Interactif-PROD.pdf|archive-date=17 August 2016|url-status=live|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last1=McGann|first1=Bill|last2=McGann|first2=Carol|title=The Story of the Tour de France: 1903\u20131964|volume=1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jxq20JskqMUC|publisher=Dog Ear Publishing|location=Indianapolis, IN|year=2006|isbn=978-1-59858-180-5|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline|Tour de France 1930|1930 Tour de France}}\n\n{{Cycling stage recaps|1930 Tour de France|1|11|12|21}}\n{{Tour de France}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tour De France}}\n[[Category:1930 Tour de France| ]]\n[[Category:1930 in road cycling]]\n[[Category:1930 in French sport|Tour de France]]\n[[Category:Tour de France by year|1930]]\n[[Category:July 1930 sports events|Tour de France]]\n", "name_user": "BaldBoris", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNotes:notelist", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1930_Tour_de_France"}
{"title_page": "BOOMERanG experiment", "text_new": "{{Infobox telescope}}\n{{Cosmology|experiments}}\nIn astronomy and [[observational cosmology]], The '''BOOMERanG experiment''' ('''Balloon Observations Of Millimetric Extragalactic Radiation ANd Geophysics''') was an experiment which measured the [[cosmic microwave background radiation]] of a part of the sky during three sub-orbital [[high-altitude balloon|(high-altitude) balloon]] flights. It was the first experiment to make large, high-fidelity images of the CMB temperature anisotropies, and is best known for the discovery in 2000 that the geometry of the universe is close to flat,<ref name=\"Nature_27Apr00\">{{cite journal|last1=de Bernardis|first1=P.|display-authors=etal|journal=Nature|date=27 April 2000|volume=404|issue=6781|pages=955\u2013959|doi=10.1038/35010035|arxiv=astro-ph/0004404 | title=A Flat Universe from High-Resolution Maps of the Cosmic Microwave Background Radiation|pmid=10801117|bibcode = 2000Natur.404..955D }}</ref> with similar results from the competing [[Millimeter Anisotropy eXperiment IMaging Array|MAXIMA]] experiment.\n\nBy using a telescope which flew at over 42,000 meters high, it was possible to reduce the atmospheric absorption of microwaves to a minimum. This allowed massive cost reduction compared to a satellite probe, though only a tiny part of the sky could be scanned.\n\nThe first was a test flight over [[North America]] in 1997. In the two subsequent flights in 1998 and 2003 the balloon was launched from [[McMurdo Station]] in the Antarctic. It was carried by the [[Polar vortex]] winds in a circle around the [[South Pole]], returning after two weeks. From this phenomenon the telescope took its name.\n\nThe BOOMERanG team was led by [[Andrew E. Lange]] of [[Caltech]] and Paolo de Bernardis of the [[University of Rome La Sapienza]].<ref name=\"NYT_27Apr00\">{{cite news |last=Glanz |first=James |date=27 April 2000 |title=Clearest Picture of Infant Universe Sees It All and Questions It, Too |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/04/27/us/clearest-picture-of-infant-universe-sees-it-all-and-questions-it-too.html?pagewanted=1 |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=2010-02-23}}</ref>\n\n==Instrumentation==\nThe experiment uses [[bolometer]]s<ref name=\"Crill\">{{cite journal|title=BOOMERANG: A Balloon-borne Millimeter Wave Telescope and Total Power Receiver for Mapping Anisotropy in the Cosmic Microwave Background|journal=[[Astrophysical Journal Supplement Series]]|volume=148|pages=527\u2013541|doi=10.1086/376894|arxiv=astro-ph/0206254|last1=Crill|first1=B. P.|display-authors=etal|date=October 2003|bibcode=2003ApJS..148..527C}}</ref> for  radiation detection. These bolometers are kept at a temperature of 0.27 [[kelvin]]. At this temperature the material has a very low heat capacity according to the [[Debye model|Debye law]], thus incoming microwave light will cause a large temperature change, proportional to the intensity of the incoming waves, which is measured with sensitive thermometers.\n\nAn off-axis 1.3-meter primary mirror<ref name=\"Crill\"/> focuses the microwaves onto the focal plane, which consist of 16 horns. These horns, operating at 145&nbsp;GHz, 245&nbsp;GHz and 345&nbsp;GHz, are arranged into 8 pixels. Only a tiny fraction of the sky can be seen concurrently, so the telescope must rotate to scan the whole field of view.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ignite-image.co.uk/boomerang-gif-booths/|title=Hire Boomerang and Animated GIF booths|accessdate= 15 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Results==\n[[Image:Boomerang CMB.jpeg|thumb|200px|right|CMB Anisotropy measured by BOOMERanG]]\nTogether with experiments like the [[Saskatoon experiment]], TOCO, MAXIMA, and others, the BOOMERanG data from 1997 and 1998 determined the angular diameter distance to the surface of last scattering with high precision.  When combined with complementary data regarding the value of [[Hubble's law|Hubble's constant]], the Boomerang data determined the [[Friedmann equations|geometry of the Universe]] to be flat,<ref name=\"Nature_27Apr00\"/> supporting the [[supernova]] evidence for the existence of [[dark energy]].  The 2003 flight of Boomerang resulted in extremely high [[signal-to-noise ratio]] maps of the CMB temperature anisotropy, and a measurement of the polarization of the [[Cosmic microwave background|CMB]].<ref name=\"MacTavish\">{{cite journal|title=Cosmological Parameters from the 2003 Flight of BOOMERANG|date=August 2006|journal=[[Astrophysical Journal]]|volume=647|pages=799\u2013812|last1=MacTavish|first1=C. J.|display-authors=etal|doi=10.1086/505558|arxiv=astro-ph/0507503|bibcode=2006ApJ...647..799M}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://stratocat.com.ar/fichas-e/1998/MCM-19981229.htm report on the 1998 flight]\n*[http://stratocat.com.ar/fichas-e/2003/MCM-20030106.htm report on the 2003 flight]\n*[https://arxiv.org/abs/astro-ph/0209132v1 Polarization Sensitive Bolometric Detector]\n\n{{CMB_experiments}}\n\n[[Category:Cosmic microwave background experiments]]\n[[Category:Balloon-borne telescopes]]\n[[Category:Astronomy in the Antarctic]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox telescope}}\n{{Cosmology|experiments}}\nIn astronomy and [[observational cosmology]], The '''BOOMERanG experiment''' ('''Balloon Observations Of Millimetric Extragalactic Radiation ANd Geophysics''') was an experiment which measured the [[cosmic microwave background radiation]] of a part of the sky during three sub-orbital [[high-altitude balloon|(high-altitude) balloon]] flights. It was the first experiment to make large, high-fidelity images of the CMB temperature anisotropies, and is best known for the discovery in 2000 that the geometry of the universe is close to flat,<ref name=\"Nature_27Apr00\">{{cite journal|last1=de Bernardis|first1=P.|display-authors=etal|journal=Nature|date=27 April 2000|volume=404|issue=6781|pages=955\u2013959|doi=10.1038/35010035|arxiv=astro-ph/0004404 | title=A Flat Universe from High-Resolution Maps of the Cosmic Microwave Background Radiation|pmid=10801117|bibcode = 2000Natur.404..955D }}</ref> with similar results from the competing [[Millimeter Anisotropy eXperiment IMaging Array|MAXIMA]] experiment.\n\nBy using a telescope which flew at over 42,000 meters high, it was possible to reduce the atmospheric absorption of microwaves to a minimum. This allowed massive cost reduction compared to a satellite probe, though only a tiny part of the sky could be scanned.\n\nThe first was a test flight over [[North America]] in 1997. In the two subsequent flights in 1998 and 2003 the balloon was launched from [[McMurdo Station]] in the Antarctic. It was carried by the [[Polar vortex]] winds in a circle around the [[South Pole]], returning after two weeks. From this phenomenon the telescope took its name.\n\nThe BOOMERanG team was led by [[Andrew E. Lange]] of [[Caltech]] and Paolo de Bernardis of the [[University of Rome La Sapienza]].<ref name=\"NYT_27Apr00\">{{cite news |last=Glanz |first=James |date=27 April 2000 |title=Clearest Picture of Infant Universe Sees It All and Questions It, Too |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/04/27/us/clearest-picture-of-infant-universe-sees-it-all-and-questions-it-too.html?pagewanted=1 |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=2010-02-23}}</ref>\n\n==Instrumentation==\nThe experiment uses [[bolometer]]s<ref name=\"Crill\">{{cite journal|title=BOOMERANG: A Balloon-borne Millimeter Wave Telescope and Total Power Receiver for Mapping Anisotropy in the Cosmic Microwave Background|journal=[[Astrophysical Journal Supplement Series]]|volume=148|pages=527\u2013541|doi=10.1086/376894|arxiv=astro-ph/0206254|last1=Crill|first1=B. P.|display-authors=etal|date=October 2003|bibcode=2003ApJS..148..527C}}</ref> for  radiation detection. These bolometers are kept at a temperature of 0.27 [[kelvin]]. At this temperature the material has a very low heat capacity according to the [[Debye model|Debye law]], thus incoming microwave light will cause a large temperature change, proportional to the intensity of the incoming waves, which is measured with sensitive thermometers.\n\nAn off-axis 1.3-meter primary mirror<ref name=\"Crill\"/> focuses the microwaves onto the focal plane, which consist of 16 horns. These horns, operating at 145&nbsp;GHz, 245&nbsp;GHz and 345&nbsp;GHz, are arranged into 8 pixels. Only a tiny fraction of the sky can be seen concurrently, so the telescope must rotate to scan the whole field of view.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ignite-images.co.uk/boomerang-gif-booths/|title=Hire Boomerang and Animated GIF booths|accessdate= 15 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Results==\n[[Image:Boomerang CMB.jpeg|thumb|200px|right|CMB Anisotropy measured by BOOMERanG]]\nTogether with experiments like the [[Saskatoon experiment]], TOCO, MAXIMA, and others, the BOOMERanG data from 1997 and 1998 determined the angular diameter distance to the surface of last scattering with high precision.  When combined with complementary data regarding the value of [[Hubble's law|Hubble's constant]], the Boomerang data determined the [[Friedmann equations|geometry of the Universe]] to be flat,<ref name=\"Nature_27Apr00\"/> supporting the [[supernova]] evidence for the existence of [[dark energy]].  The 2003 flight of Boomerang resulted in extremely high [[signal-to-noise ratio]] maps of the CMB temperature anisotropy, and a measurement of the polarization of the [[Cosmic microwave background|CMB]].<ref name=\"MacTavish\">{{cite journal|title=Cosmological Parameters from the 2003 Flight of BOOMERANG|date=August 2006|journal=[[Astrophysical Journal]]|volume=647|pages=799\u2013812|last1=MacTavish|first1=C. J.|display-authors=etal|doi=10.1086/505558|arxiv=astro-ph/0507503|bibcode=2006ApJ...647..799M}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://stratocat.com.ar/fichas-e/1998/MCM-19981229.htm report on the 1998 flight]\n*[http://stratocat.com.ar/fichas-e/2003/MCM-20030106.htm report on the 2003 flight]\n*[https://arxiv.org/abs/astro-ph/0209132v1 Polarization Sensitive Bolometric Detector]\n\n{{CMB_experiments}}\n\n[[Category:Cosmic microwave background experiments]]\n[[Category:Balloon-borne telescopes]]\n[[Category:Astronomy in the Antarctic]]\n", "name_user": "AaronL1971", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BOOMERanG_experiment"}
{"title_page": "Squeeze Play!", "text_new": "{{short description|1979 film by Michael Herz, Lloyd Kaufman}}\n{{refimprove|date=August 2018}}\n{{other uses|Squeeze play (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Squeeze Play!\n| image          = Squeeze play cover.jpg\n| caption        = DVD cover\n| director       = [[Lloyd Kaufman]]\n| producer       = [[Michael Herz (producer)|Michael Herz]]<br>[[Lloyd Kaufman]]\n| writer         = [[Lloyd Kaufman]]<br>Charles Kaufman<br>Haim Pekelis\n| starring       = Jim Harris<br>[[Jennifer Hetrick]]<br>Rick Gitlin<br>Helen Campitelli<br>[[Al Corley]]\n| music          =\n| cinematography = Richard Hicks\n| editing        =\n| distributor    = [[Troma Entertainment]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1980|1|16}}\n| runtime        = 88 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $115,000\n| gross          =\n}}\n\n'''''Squeeze Play!''''' is a 1980 American [[comedy film]] directed by [[Lloyd Kaufman]].\n\n==Plot==\nA group of [[New Jersey]] women, upset over their boyfriends' tendency to pay more attention to softball than their love lives, decide to beat them at their own game...literally. The girls form their own softball team and challenge the men to a match out on the field. The men initially scoff at the idea, but soon grow nervous when they worry that they'll lose face if they refuse to play.\n\n==Production==\nThe idea of ''Squeeze Play!'' came from a suggestion that Kaufman and Herz should make a movie about a women's [[softball]] team and their amorous adventures. Kaufman added the comedy element, and along with his brother Charles and screenwriter Haim Pekelis, a 75-page screenplay was finally worked out; the Kaufmans provided the ideas for sight gags and jokes, and Pekelis worked out the plot.\n\n==Reception==\nOnce ''Squeeze Play!'' was completed, the reactions were almost unanimously negative. Major studios refused to distribute it, and two of the film's executive producers demanded to have their names taken off of it.\n\n''Squeeze Play!'' finally made its theatrical debut as a double feature with ''[[The In-Laws (1979 film)|The In-Laws]]'' in [[Norfolk, Virginia]] to tremendous success. The film built up a steady following in Virginia before being widely distributed nationwide.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://catalog.afi.com/Film/56879-SQUEEZE-PLAY?sid=9430f0c7-04ec-43a3-ab04-51caa09064f5&sr=4.8295093&cp=1&pos=0#1 |title=Squeeze Play - History |website=[[AFI Catalog of Feature Films]] |publisher=[[American Film Institute]] |accessdate=December 3, 2018 }}</ref> The film was constantly in [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]\u2019s top 50 list.\n\n[[Janet Maslin]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' called it \"a zesty movie of its kind, though its kind is bound to seem stupid to some and objectionable to others ... the actors are fresh and likable, and at least they don't stand still long enough to wear out their welcome.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Maslin |first1=Janet |title='SQUEEZE PLAY,' BURLESQUE-STYLE BASEBALL |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1981/05/08/movies/squeeze-play-burlesque-style-baseball.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=13 August 2018 |date=May 8, 1981}}</ref> ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' wrote that the film \"does to softball what '[[Animal House]]' and '[[Meatballs (film)|Meatballs]]' did to college and summer camp. But if they rated tastelessness, this battle of the sexes on the diamond would handily outscore the other bawdy pics hands down.\"<ref>\"Film Reviews: Squeeze Play\". ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]''. May 20, 1981. p. 24.</ref> [[Gene Siskel]] of the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' gave the film zero stars out of four and called it \"not much more professional than a home movie.\" He revealed that he walked out on the film, \"which is something I rarely do more than once or twice a year. But when one of the male characters reached into his nose and pulled out some snot and placed it in the beard of a bully, I had enough.\"<ref>[[Gene Siskel|Siskel, Gene]] (May 4, 1981). \"'Friday the 13th' sequel reverts to old, disgusting tactics\". ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. Section 2, p. 3.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{imdb title|id=0081552|title=Squeeze Play!}}\n\n{{Lloyd Kaufman}}\n\n[[Category:1979 films]]\n[[Category:1970s sex comedy films]]\n[[Category:1970s sports comedy films]]\n[[Category:American sex comedy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Lloyd Kaufman]]\n[[Category:Films set in New Jersey]]\n[[Category:American baseball films]]\n[[Category:Troma Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:Teen sex comedy films]]\n\n\n{{erotic-comedy-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1979 film by Michael Herz, Lloyd Kaufman}}\n{{refimprove|date=August 2018}}\n{{other uses|Squeeze play (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Squeeze Play!\n| image          = Squeeze play cover.jpg\n| caption        = DVD cover\n| director       = [[Lloyd Kaufman]]\n| producer       = [[Michael Herz (producer)|Michael Herz]]<br>[[Lloyd Kaufman]]\n| writer         = [[Lloyd Kaufman]]<br>Charles Kaufman<br>Haim Pekelis\n| starring       = Jim Harris<br>[[Jennifer Hetrick]]<br>Rick Gitlin<br>Helen Campitelli<br>[[Al Corley]]\n| music          =\n| cinematography = Richard Hicks\n| editing        =\n| distributor    = [[Troma Entertainment]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1980|1|16}}\n| runtime        = 88 minutes\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $115,000\n| gross          =\n}}\n\n'''''Squeeze Play!''''' is a 1980 American [[comedy film]] directed by [[Lloyd Kaufman]].\n\n==Plot==\nA group of [[New Jersey]] women, upset over their boyfriends' tendency to pay more attention to softball than their love lives, decide to beat them at their own game...literally. The girls form their own softball team and challenge the men to a match out on the field. The men initially scoff at the idea, but soon grow nervous when they worry that they'll lose face if they refuse to play.\n\n==Production==\nThe idea of ''Squeeze Play!'' came from a suggestion that Kaufman and Herz should make a movie about a women\u2019s [[softball]] team and their amorous adventures. Kaufman added the comedy element, and along with his brother Charles and screenwriter Haim Pekelis, a 75-page screenplay was finally worked out; the Kaufmans provided the ideas for sight gags and jokes, and Pekelis worked out the plot.\n\n==Reception==\nOnce ''Squeeze Play!'' was completed, the reactions were almost unanimously negative. Major studios refused to distribute it, and two of the film\u2019s executive producers demanded to have their names taken off of it.\n\n''Squeeze Play!'' finally made its theatrical debut as a double feature with ''[[The In-Laws (1979 film)|The In-Laws]]'' in [[Norfolk, Virginia]] to tremendous success. The film built up a steady following in Virginia before being widely distributed nationwide.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://catalog.afi.com/Film/56879-SQUEEZE-PLAY?sid=9430f0c7-04ec-43a3-ab04-51caa09064f5&sr=4.8295093&cp=1&pos=0#1 |title=Squeeze Play - History |website=[[AFI Catalog of Feature Films]] |publisher=[[American Film Institute]] |accessdate=December 3, 2018 }}</ref> The film was constantly in [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]\u2019s top 50 list.\n\n[[Janet Maslin]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' called it \"a zesty movie of its kind, though its kind is bound to seem stupid to some and objectionable to others ... the actors are fresh and likable, and at least they don't stand still long enough to wear out their welcome.\"<ref>{{cite web |last1=Maslin |first1=Janet |title='SQUEEZE PLAY,' BURLESQUE-STYLE BASEBALL |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1981/05/08/movies/squeeze-play-burlesque-style-baseball.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=13 August 2018 |date=May 8, 1981}}</ref> ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' wrote that the film \"does to softball what '[[Animal House]]' and '[[Meatballs (film)|Meatballs]]' did to college and summer camp. But if they rated tastelessness, this battle of the sexes on the diamond would handily outscore the other bawdy pics hands down.\"<ref>\"Film Reviews: Squeeze Play\". ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]''. May 20, 1981. p. 24.</ref> [[Gene Siskel]] of the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' gave the film zero stars out of four and called it \"not much more professional than a home movie.\" He revealed that he walked out on the film, \"which is something I rarely do more than once or twice a year. But when one of the male characters reached into his nose and pulled out some snot and placed it in the beard of a bully, I had enough.\"<ref>[[Gene Siskel|Siskel, Gene]] (May 4, 1981). \"'Friday the 13th' sequel reverts to old, disgusting tactics\". ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''. Section 2, p. 3.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{imdb title|id=0081552|title=Squeeze Play!}}\n\n{{Lloyd Kaufman}}\n\n[[Category:1979 films]]\n[[Category:1970s sex comedy films]]\n[[Category:1970s sports comedy films]]\n[[Category:American sex comedy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Lloyd Kaufman]]\n[[Category:Films set in New Jersey]]\n[[Category:American baseball films]]\n[[Category:Troma Entertainment films]]\n[[Category:Teen sex comedy films]]\n\n\n{{erotic-comedy-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Squeeze_Play!"}
{"title_page": "The Sex Thief", "text_new": "{{short description|1973 film by Martin Campbell}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Sex Thief\n| image          = The Sex Thief.jpg\n| director       = [[Martin Campbell]]\n| producer       = [[Tudor Gates]]\n| writer         = [[Michael Armstrong (cinematographer)|Michael Armstrong]]<br>[[Tudor Gates]]\n| starring       = [[David Warbeck]]<br>[[Diane Keen]]<br>[[Christopher Biggins]]\n| music\t         = [[Mike Vickers]]\n| cinematography = [[Grenville Middleton]]\n| editing        = [[Peter Musgrave]]\n| distributor    = LMG\n| released       = {{film date|df=yes|1973|7}}\n| runtime        = 89 minutes\n| country        = United Kingdom\n| language       = English\n| budget         =\n| gross          =\n| preceded_by    =\n| followed_by    =\n}}\n'''''The Sex Thief''''' is a 1973 British sex film starring [[David Warbeck]], [[Diane Keen]] and [[Christopher Biggins]]. It was an early film credit for director [[Martin Campbell]].\n\nThe film was released in North America (in January 1976) as ''Her Family Jewels'', with added [[Hardcore pornography|hardcore]] inserts performed by stand-ins for the original cast members.\n\nKeen, quoted in the book ''The Worlds Greatest Scandals of the 20th Century'', claimed: \"Times were pretty hard and this is a comedy which I am not ashamed at having made. But it was bought by a company, which drafted in other actresses to make it look like I was doing erotic things from start to finish. It became incredibly filthy.\" The hardcore version was later released on video in The Netherlands (under the name ''Handful of Diamonds'').    \nThe film was written by [[Tudor Gates]] and [[Michael Armstrong (cinematographer)|Michael Armstrong]] under the name Edward Hyde.\n\nDuring the 2007 series of ''[[I'm a Celebrity... Get Me Out of Here!]]'', Biggins failed to get a question right about his character's name in the film as part of a [[bush tucker|bushtucker]] trial. He groaned, \"''The Sex Thief'', god, that was a million years ago.\"\n\nThe soft version of the film was shown on Movies for Men (on Sky television) on 24 April 2008.\n\n==Plot==\nGrant Henry ([[David Warbeck]]), a writer of trashy paperbacks like ''The Dirty and the Dying'', moonlights as a masked jewel thief who is usually caught in the act but is able to get away with his crimes by luring his female victims to bed. After these women lie to the police about the thief's identity (\"who could disguise himself as a clubfooted coloured midget one week and a 6\u20326\u2033 Russian with a [[Cleft lip and cleft palate|harelip]] the next\") and seem to want to get burgled again, the Inspector in charge of the case ([[Terence Edmond]]) and an insurance investigator trained in [[Chinese martial arts|kung fu]] ([[Diane Keen]]) decide to lay a trap for the thief.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[David Warbeck]] ....  Grant Henry\n*[[Diane Keen]] ....  Judy Martin\n*[[Terence Edmond]] ....  Insp. Robert Smith\n*Deirdre Costello ....  Jezebel Lorraine (as Linda Coombes)\n*[[Michael Armstrong (cinematographer)|Michael Armstrong]] ....  Sgt. Plinth\n*[[Christopher Neil]] ....  Guy Hammond\n*[[Jennifer Westbrook]] ....  Emily Barrow (as Jenny Westbrook)\n*[[Harvey Hall (actor)|Harvey Hall]] ....  Jacobi\n*[[Christopher Biggins]] ....  Lord 'Porky' Prescott\n*[[Christopher Mitchell (actor)|Christopher Mitchell]] ....  Ian Wensleydale\n*[[Eric Deacon]] ....  Crabshaw\n\n==Censorship history==\n''The Sex Thief'' was heavily cut by the [[British Board of Film Classification|British Board of Film Censors]] on its original release; cuts were made to the scene where the naked girl dances in front of Grant, and the inter-cutting between a further sex scene and a wrestling match. The film's speeded-up sex scene was \u2018considerably reduced\u2019, as was the scene where a handcuffed Grant is seduced by Judy. The current US and UK DVD releases are uncut.\n\n==Appearance in Texas murder trial==\nThe movie appeared as incriminating evidence in the 1987 trial against [[Michael Morton (criminal justice)|Michael Morton]], wrongly convicted for murdering his wife. It was shown to the jury, in an effort to make them negatively disposed to Morton.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Innocent Man|url=http://www.texasmonthly.com/2012-11-01/feature2-6.php}}</ref>\n\n==Alternative version==\nThe US ''Her Family Jewels''/''Handful of Diamonds'' version runs approximately 81 minutes (as opposed to the original 89-minute running time) and adds [[Hardcore pornography|hardcore]] inserts<ref>Sheridan,Simon (2011). ''Keeping the British End Up: Four Decades of Saucy Cinema''. Titan Books Ltd</ref> to every sex scene as well as an innocuous scene where the characters played by Terence Edmond and Diane Keen discuss the thief in a crowded pub, in which the hardcore inserts imply the two characters are [[Masturbation|masturbating]] each other under the table. ''Her Family Jewels'' deletes several narrative scenes that appear in the original version of the film\u2014most notably the end credits and a subplot involving two detectives trying to sell [[pornographic film]]s\u2014but adds several newly shot hardcore scenes, in which footage of David Warbeck (taken from elsewhere in the film) has been briefly inserted. These scenes are scored to the pop song \"Well Here I Go\", which does not appear in the original film.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{IMDb title|0070674}}\n\n{{Martin Campbell}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sex Thief, The}}\n[[Category:1973 films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British sex comedy films]]\n[[Category:Directorial debut films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Martin Campbell]]\n[[Category:1970s sex comedy films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1973 film by Martin Campbell}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Sex Thief\n| image          = The Sex Thief.jpg\n| director       = [[Martin Campbell]]\n| producer       = [[Tudor Gates]]\n| writer         = [[Michael Armstrong (cinematographer)|Michael Armstrong]]<br>[[Tudor Gates]]\n| starring       = [[David Warbeck]]<br>[[Diane Keen]]<br>[[Christopher Biggins]]\n| music\t         = [[Mike Vickers]]\n| cinematography = [[Grenville Middleton]]\n| editing        = [[Peter Musgrave]]\n| distributor    = LMG\n| released       = {{film date|df=yes|1973|7}}\n| runtime        = 89 minutes\n| country        = United Kingdom\n| language       = English\n| budget         =\n| gross          =\n| preceded_by    =\n| followed_by    =\n}}\n'''''The Sex Thief''''' is a 1973 British sex film starring [[David Warbeck]], [[Diane Keen]] and [[Christopher Biggins]]. It was an early film credit for director [[Martin Campbell]].\n\nThe film was released in North America (in January 1976) as ''Her Family Jewels'', with added [[Hardcore pornography|hardcore]] inserts performed by stand-ins for the original cast members.\n\nKeen, quoted in the book ''The Worlds Greatest Scandals of the 20th Century'', claimed: \"Times were pretty hard and this is a comedy which I am not ashamed at having made. But it was bought by a company, which drafted in other actresses to make it look like I was doing erotic things from start to finish. It became incredibly filthy.\" The hardcore version was later released on video in The Netherlands (under the name ''Handful of Diamonds'').    \nThe film was written by [[Tudor Gates]] and [[Michael Armstrong (cinematographer)|Michael Armstrong]] under the name Edward Hyde.\n\nDuring the 2007 series of ''[[I'm a Celebrity... Get Me Out of Here!]]'', Biggins failed to get a question right about his character's name in the film as part of a [[bush tucker|bushtucker]] trial. He groaned, \"''The Sex Thief'', god, that was a million years ago.\"\n\nThe soft version of the film was shown on Movies for Men (on Sky television) on 24 April 2008.\n\n==Plot==\nGrant Henry ([[David Warbeck]]), a writer of trashy paperbacks like ''The Dirty and the Dying'', moonlights as a masked jewel thief who is usually caught in the act but is able to get away with his crimes by luring his female victims to bed. After these women lie to the police about the thief\u2019s identity (\"who could disguise himself as a clubfooted coloured midget one week and a 6\u20326\u2033 Russian with a [[Cleft lip and cleft palate|harelip]] the next\") and seem to want to get burgled again, the Inspector in charge of the case ([[Terence Edmond]]) and an insurance investigator trained in [[Chinese martial arts|kung fu]] ([[Diane Keen]]) decide to lay a trap for the thief.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[David Warbeck]] ....  Grant Henry\n*[[Diane Keen]] ....  Judy Martin\n*[[Terence Edmond]] ....  Insp. Robert Smith\n*Deirdre Costello ....  Jezebel Lorraine (as Linda Coombes)\n*[[Michael Armstrong (cinematographer)|Michael Armstrong]] ....  Sgt. Plinth\n*[[Christopher Neil]] ....  Guy Hammond\n*[[Jennifer Westbrook]] ....  Emily Barrow (as Jenny Westbrook)\n*[[Harvey Hall (actor)|Harvey Hall]] ....  Jacobi\n*[[Christopher Biggins]] ....  Lord 'Porky' Prescott\n*[[Christopher Mitchell (actor)|Christopher Mitchell]] ....  Ian Wensleydale\n*[[Eric Deacon]] ....  Crabshaw\n\n==Censorship history==\n''The Sex Thief'' was heavily cut by the [[British Board of Film Classification|British Board of Film Censors]] on its original release; cuts were made to the scene where the naked girl dances in front of Grant, and the inter-cutting between a further sex scene and a wrestling match. The film's speeded-up sex scene was \u2018considerably reduced\u2019, as was the scene where a handcuffed Grant is seduced by Judy. The current US and UK DVD releases are uncut.\n\n==Appearance in Texas murder trial==\nThe movie appeared as incriminating evidence in the 1987 trial against [[Michael Morton (criminal justice)|Michael Morton]], wrongly convicted for murdering his wife. It was shown to the jury, in an effort to make them negatively disposed to Morton.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Innocent Man|url=http://www.texasmonthly.com/2012-11-01/feature2-6.php}}</ref>\n\n==Alternative version==\nThe US ''Her Family Jewels''/''Handful of Diamonds'' version runs approximately 81 minutes (as opposed to the original 89-minute running time) and adds [[Hardcore pornography|hardcore]] inserts<ref>Sheridan,Simon (2011). ''Keeping the British End Up: Four Decades of Saucy Cinema''. Titan Books Ltd</ref> to every sex scene as well as an innocuous scene where the characters played by Terence Edmond and Diane Keen discuss the thief in a crowded pub, in which the hardcore inserts imply the two characters are [[Masturbation|masturbating]] each other under the table. ''Her Family Jewels'' deletes several narrative scenes that appear in the original version of the film\u2014most notably the end credits and a subplot involving two detectives trying to sell [[pornographic film]]s\u2014but adds several newly shot hardcore scenes, in which footage of David Warbeck (taken from elsewhere in the film) has been briefly inserted. These scenes are scored to the pop song \"Well Here I Go\", which does not appear in the original film.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{IMDb title|0070674}}\n\n{{Martin Campbell}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sex Thief, The}}\n[[Category:1973 films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British sex comedy films]]\n[[Category:Directorial debut films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Martin Campbell]]\n[[Category:1970s sex comedy films]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePlot:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Sex_Thief"}
{"title_page": "Secrets of a Superstud", "text_new": "{{short description|1975 film}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{More footnotes|date=July 2017}}\n{{Refimprove|date=July 2017}}}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Secrets of a Super Stud\n| director       = Morton M Lewis<br>Alan Selwyn\n| producer       = Morton M Lewis\n| writer         = Gerry Levy<br>Morton M Lewis<br>Alan Selwyn\n| starring       = Anthony Kenyon<br>[[Mark Jones (actor)|Mark Jones]]<br>[[Margaret Burton (actress)|Margaret Burton]]<br>Raymond Young<br>Maggie Wright<br>\n| music          = [[John Carter (musician)|John Shakespeare]]<br>Derek Warne<br>[[Ross MacManus]]\n| editing        = [[Peter Pitt]]\n| distributor    = [[Butcher's Film Service]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1976}}\n| runtime        = 90 minutes\n| country        = United Kingdom\n| language       = English\n| budget         =\n| gross          =\n}}\n\n'''''Secrets of a Super Stud''''', also known as '''''It's Getting Harder All the Time''''' and '''''Naughty Girls on the Loose''''', is a 1976 British sex comedy film, one of many to be also filmed in a hardcore version for export. It was shot at [[Twickenham Film Studios]] under the title \"Custer\u2019s Thirteen\", the general release prints and the hardcore version were processed at Kay Labs at Highbury, North London.  \n\nDetails of the film's hardcore version were leaked by the magazine ''[[Cinema X]]'' (July 1976; vol.8. no5, page 22), after the magazine had become disillusioned by certain British filmmakers refusal to acknowledge they were shooting hardcore \"at Cinema X magazine we know which directors have shot porno; we\u2019ve talked to their stars.  But its little use quoting them, when the directors, producers, above all their distributors, vociferously deny everything.  We prefer honesty in our pages.\"\n\n==Plot==\nCuster Firkinshaw (Anthony Kenyon) the owner of 'Bare Monthly' Magazine is up to his neck in dirty pictures and sexy secretaries.  His hedonistic ways are however temporary halted when his Uncle Charlie dies and Custer is pitted against his relatives. His Uncle leaves Custer a fortune in the will, but only on the condition that he marries and has a child within 12 months, otherwise it all goes to his relatives. Custer's money grabbing Aunt Sophie (Margaret Burton) knows only too well about Custer's swinging ways, so keep tabs on him by hiring a crooked private detective Bernie Selby (Alan Selwyn).  When Custer visits a doctor both parties discover that due to Custer's oversexed lifestyle he's only got 13 units of 'sexually activity' left, meaning he has only 13 more attempts to father a child.  \n\nWhen Aunt Sophie learns of this she plans to stitch Custer up calling on Selby to hire girls to seduce Custer and use up those potent 13 units of sexual activity.  Thereon in, it's a race against time as Custer tries to find a suitable bride to impregnate while Selby's girls pose as cat burglars, 'lost' neighbours and even drag up as meter inspectors in order to catch lure Custer into temptation.\n\n==Cast==\n*Anthony Kenyon as Custer Firkinshaw\n*[[Mark Jones (actor)|Mark Jones]] as Peter\n*Alan Selwyn as Bernie Selby\n*[[Margaret Burton (actress)|Margaret Burton]] as Aunt Sophie\n*Raymond Young as Uncle Clifton\n*Maggie Wright as Sybil\n*Jennifer Westbrook as Miranda\n*David Rayner as Dr. Lemmon\n*[[Michael Cronin (actor)|Michael Cronin]] as Dr. Halldenburger\n*Bobby Sparrow as Beryl\n*Juliet Groves as Julie\n*[[Jeannette Charles]] as The Lady\n*[[Cosey Fanni Tutti]] as Gas Girl\n\n==Songs==\n''Secrets of a Super Stud'' also contains several songs that relate the film's plot as if it were a western, using many double-entendres (\u2018Custer\u2019s last stand\u2019, \u2018quick on the drawers\u2019). The songs were written by [[Ross MacManus]], and performed by MacManus and Laura Lee. They include:\n\n* \"It\u2019s Getting Harder All the Time\" (sung by MacManus)\n* \"Custer Firkinshaw\" (sung by MacManus)\n* \"This is Your Last Stand\" (sung by Lee)\n\n==References==\n*Simon Sheridan, ''Keeping the British End Up: Four Decades of Saucy Cinema'' (2011) (fourth edition) Titan Books, {{ISBN|9780857682796}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0318674|title=Secrets of a Superstud}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110722005119/http://www.pre-cert.co.uk/cgi-bin/cms/Film/40256 British Video Cover]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090208202054/http://pre-cert.co.uk/cgi-bin/cms/Film/43822 Alternative British Video Cover]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Secrets Of A Superstud}}\n[[Category:1976 films]]\n[[Category:British sex comedy films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:1970s sex comedy films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1975 film}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{More footnotes|date=July 2017}}\n{{Refimprove|date=July 2017}}}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2016}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Secrets of a Super Stud\n| director       = Morton M Lewis<br>Alan Selwyn\n| producer       = Morton M Lewis\n| writer         = Gerry Levy<br>Morton M Lewis<br>Alan Selwyn\n| starring       = Anthony Kenyon<br>[[Mark Jones (actor)|Mark Jones]]<br>[[Margaret Burton (actress)|Margaret Burton]]<br>Raymond Young<br>Maggie Wright<br>\n| music          = [[John Carter (musician)|John Shakespeare]]<br>Derek Warne<br>[[Ross MacManus]]\n| editing        = [[Peter Pitt]]\n| distributor    = [[Butcher's Film Service]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1976}}\n| runtime        = 90 minutes\n| country        = United Kingdom\n| language       = English\n| budget         =\n| gross          =\n}}\n\n'''''Secrets of a Super Stud''''', also known as '''''It's Getting Harder All the Time''''' and '''''Naughty Girls on the Loose''''', is a 1976 British sex comedy film, one of many to be also filmed in a hardcore version for export. It was shot at [[Twickenham Film Studios]] under the title \"Custer\u2019s Thirteen\", the general release prints and the hardcore version were processed at Kay Labs at Highbury, North London.  \n\nDetails of the film\u2019s hardcore version were leaked by the magazine ''[[Cinema X]]'' (July 1976; vol.8. no5, page 22), after the magazine had become disillusioned by certain British filmmakers refusal to acknowledge they were shooting hardcore \"at Cinema X magazine we know which directors have shot porno; we\u2019ve talked to their stars.  But its little use quoting them, when the directors, producers, above all their distributors, vociferously deny everything.  We prefer honesty in our pages.\"\n\n==Plot==\nCuster Firkinshaw (Anthony Kenyon) the owner of 'Bare Monthly' Magazine is up to his neck in dirty pictures and sexy secretaries.  His hedonistic ways are however temporary halted when his Uncle Charlie dies and Custer is pitted against his relatives. His Uncle leaves Custer a fortune in the will, but only on the condition that he marries and has a child within 12 months, otherwise it all goes to his relatives. Custer\u2019s money grabbing Aunt Sophie (Margaret Burton) knows only too well about Custer's swinging ways, so keep tabs on him by hiring a crooked private detective Bernie Selby (Alan Selwyn).  When Custer visits a doctor both parties discover that due to Custer's oversexed lifestyle he's only got 13 units of 'sexually activity' left, meaning he has only 13 more attempts to father a child.  \n\nWhen Aunt Sophie learns of this she plans to stitch Custer up calling on Selby to hire girls to seduce Custer and use up those potent 13 units of sexual activity.  Thereon in, it's a race against time as Custer tries to find a suitable bride to impregnate while Selby\u2019s girls pose as cat burglars, 'lost' neighbours and even drag up as meter inspectors in order to catch lure Custer into temptation.\n\n==Cast==\n*Anthony Kenyon as Custer Firkinshaw\n*[[Mark Jones (actor)|Mark Jones]] as Peter\n*Alan Selwyn as Bernie Selby\n*[[Margaret Burton (actress)|Margaret Burton]] as Aunt Sophie\n*Raymond Young as Uncle Clifton\n*Maggie Wright as Sybil\n*Jennifer Westbrook as Miranda\n*David Rayner as Dr. Lemmon\n*[[Michael Cronin (actor)|Michael Cronin]] as Dr. Halldenburger\n*Bobby Sparrow as Beryl\n*Juliet Groves as Julie\n*[[Jeannette Charles]] as The Lady\n*[[Cosey Fanni Tutti]] as Gas Girl\n\n==Songs==\n''Secrets of a Super Stud'' also contains several songs that relate the film\u2019s plot as if it were a western, using many double-entendres (\u2018Custer\u2019s last stand\u2019, \u2018quick on the drawers\u2019). The songs were written by [[Ross MacManus]], and performed by MacManus and Laura Lee. They include:\n\n* \"It\u2019s Getting Harder All the Time\" (sung by MacManus)\n* \"Custer Firkinshaw\" (sung by MacManus)\n* \"This is Your Last Stand\" (sung by Lee)\n\n==References==\n*Simon Sheridan, ''Keeping the British End Up: Four Decades of Saucy Cinema'' (2011) (fourth edition) Titan Books, {{ISBN|9780857682796}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0318674|title=Secrets of a Superstud}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110722005119/http://www.pre-cert.co.uk/cgi-bin/cms/Film/40256 British Video Cover]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090208202054/http://pre-cert.co.uk/cgi-bin/cms/Film/43822 Alternative British Video Cover]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Secrets Of A Superstud}}\n[[Category:1976 films]]\n[[Category:British sex comedy films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:1970s sex comedy films]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (4)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Secrets_of_a_Superstud"}
{"title_page": "Odd B\u00f8rretzen", "text_new": "{{distinguish|text=[[Odd B\u00f8rresen]], a Norwegian linguist, preacher, and missionary}}\n{{expand Norwegian|Odd B\u00f8rretzen|date=August 2012}}\n\n[[File:Odd B\u00f8rretzen.jpg|thumb|right |200 px |Odd B\u00f8rretzen in 2005]]\n'''Odd Lunde B\u00f8rretzen''' (21 November 1926&nbsp;\u2013 3 November 2012)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=10047536 |title=Odd B\u00f8rretzen er d\u00f8d - VG Nett |publisher=Vg.no |date=2012-01-01 |accessdate=2012-11-03}}</ref> was a [[Norwegians|Norwegian]] author, illustrator, translator, and one of the most significant text writers, folk singers and artists in [[Norway]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://snl.no/.nbl_biografi/Odd_B%C3%B8rretzen/utdypning |title=Biography - Store Norske Leksikon}} (in Norwegian)</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.worldcat.org/search?q=Odd+B%C3%B8rretzen&fq=dt%3Abks+%3E+ap%3A%22b%C3%B8rretzen%2C+odd%22&dblist=638&start=11&qt=page_number_link|title=Odd B\u00f8rretzen |accessdate= 27 March 2010|author= |authorlink= |date= |year= |publisher=WorldCat.org |pages= |language= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |quote= }}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\n\nB\u00f8rretzen was born in [[Fister]] in the [[Hjelmeland]] municipality as the son of the preacher [[Jacob B\u00f8rretzen]].<ref>[https://nbl.snl.no/Odd_B%C3%B8rretzen ''Norsk biografisk leksikon'': Odd B\u00f8rretzen] {{in lang|no}}</ref> When Odd was three years old, his family moved to [[Grorud]] in [[Oslo]]; his childhood is related in the self-biographic ''Min barndoms verden'' (My Childhood World, 1997; filmed as ''[[Odd Little Man|Da jeg traff Jesus \u2026 med sprettert]]'', 2000). Later in life, between 1946 and 1952, he worked as a telegrapher among other things.\n\nHe debuted as an author in 1959 with his self-illustrated children's book ''Byen som laget brannbil'' (The city that made a firetruck). He released his first [[record album]] in 1974, and this was a product of many years of collaboration with the famous Norwegian folk singer and lyricist [[Alf Cranner]]. In 1981 he started a comprehensive cooperation with another famous Norwegian folk singer and lyricist [[Lars Martin Myhre]], that would later have a profound impact in the musical life of Norway. B\u00f8rretzen's play ''Synd og skam'' (Pity and shame) was shown on Teater [[Ibsen]] in 1994, his [[manuscript]]s always written by hand are sharp witty and always with an edge into current issues or universal everyday life.\n\nHe is well known for his many performances with [[Julius Hougen]] on radio and television as Braathen, a pensioner. They received a strong reaction to the so-called pensioner sketches, and therefore B\u00f8rretzen decided to stop performing them due to bad conscience. He also was the narrator for the animation series ''Kalles klatretre'' (Kalle's Climbing Tree) on [[NRK]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0127228/ |title=Odd B\u00f8rretzen |accessdate=27 March 2010 |author= |authorlink= |date= |year= |publisher=Internet Movie Database |pages= |language= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |quote= }}</ref>\n\nB\u00f8rretzen lived in [[Holmestrand]]. He lived with Eva B\u00f8dtker-N\u00e6ss, a sculptor, for over thirty years.<ref>[http://www.vg.no/rampelys/bok/eva-vil-alltid-vaere-min-kone/a/108803/ Lerum, May Grethe. 2005. Eva vil alltid v\u00e6re min kone. ''Verdens Gang'' (October 28).] {{in lang|no}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nOdd B\u00f8rretzen won the [[Herman Wildenvey Poetry Award]] in 2005.<ref>[http://litteraturivestfold.origo.no/-/bulletin/show/740966_wildenveyprisen-2012?ref=checkpoint Wildenveyprisen 2012. 2012. ''Litteratur i Vestfold'' (June 6).]</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n{{commons}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=0127228}}\n\n{{Portal |Children's literature}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Borretzen, Odd}}\n[[Category:1926 births]]\n[[Category:2012 deaths]]\n[[Category:Norwegian children's writers]]\n[[Category:Norwegian illustrators]]\n[[Category:Spellemannprisen winners]]\n[[Category:Leonard Statuette winners]]\n[[Category:Deaths from pneumonia]]\n[[Category:20th-century Norwegian dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Norwegian male dramatists and playwrights]]\n\n{{Norway-artist-stub}}\n{{illustrator-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|text=[[Odd B\u00f8rresen]], a Norwegian linguist, preacher, and missionary}}\n{{expand Norwegian|Odd B\u00f8rretzen|date=August 2012}}\n\n[[File:Odd B\u00f8rretzen.jpg|thumb |right |200 px |Odd B\u00f8rretzen in 2005]]\n'''Odd Lunde B\u00f8rretzen''' (21 November 1926&nbsp;\u2013 3 November 2012)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vg.no/nyheter/innenriks/artikkel.php?artid=10047536 |title=Odd B\u00f8rretzen er d\u00f8d - VG Nett |publisher=Vg.no |date=2012-01-01 |accessdate=2012-11-03}}</ref> was a [[Norwegians|Norwegian]] author, illustrator, translator, and one of the most significant text writers, folk singers and artists in [[Norway]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://snl.no/.nbl_biografi/Odd_B%C3%B8rretzen/utdypning |title=Biography - Store Norske Leksikon}} (in Norwegian)</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.worldcat.org/search?q=Odd+B%C3%B8rretzen&fq=dt%3Abks+%3E+ap%3A%22b%C3%B8rretzen%2C+odd%22&dblist=638&start=11&qt=page_number_link|title=Odd B\u00f8rretzen |accessdate= 27 March 2010|author= |authorlink= |date= |year= |publisher=WorldCat.org |pages= |language= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |quote= }}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\n\nB\u00f8rretzen was born in [[Fister]] in the [[Hjelmeland]] municipality as the son of the preacher [[Jacob B\u00f8rretzen]].<ref>[https://nbl.snl.no/Odd_B%C3%B8rretzen ''Norsk biografisk leksikon'': Odd B\u00f8rretzen] {{in lang|no}}</ref> When Odd was three years old, his family moved to [[Grorud]] in [[Oslo]]; his childhood is related in the self-biographic ''Min barndoms verden'' (My Childhood World, 1997; filmed as ''[[Odd Little Man|Da jeg traff Jesus \u2026 med sprettert]]'', 2000). Later in life, between 1946 and 1952, he worked as a telegrapher among other things.\n\nHe debuted as an author in 1959 with his self-illustrated children's book ''Byen som laget brannbil'' (The city that made a firetruck). He released his first [[record album]] in 1974, and this was a product of many years of collaboration with the famous Norwegian folk singer and lyricist [[Alf Cranner]]. In 1981 he started a comprehensive cooperation with another famous Norwegian folk singer and lyricist [[Lars Martin Myhre]], that would later have a profound impact in the musical life of Norway. B\u00f8rretzen's play ''Synd og skam'' (Pity and shame) was shown on Teater [[Ibsen]] in 1994, his [[manuscript]]s always written by hand are sharp witty and always with an edge into current issues or universal everyday life.\n\nHe is well known for his many performances with [[Julius Hougen]] on radio and television as Braathen, a pensioner. They received a strong reaction to the so-called pensioner sketches, and therefore B\u00f8rretzen decided to stop performing them due to bad conscience. He also was the narrator for the animation series ''Kalles klatretre'' (Kalle's Climbing Tree) on [[NRK]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0127228/ |title=Odd B\u00f8rretzen |accessdate=27 March 2010 |author= |authorlink= |date= |year= |publisher=Internet Movie Database |pages= |language= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |quote= }}</ref>\n\nB\u00f8rretzen lived in [[Holmestrand]]. He lived with Eva B\u00f8dtker-N\u00e6ss, a sculptor, for over thirty years.<ref>[http://www.vg.no/rampelys/bok/eva-vil-alltid-vaere-min-kone/a/108803/ Lerum, May Grethe. 2005. Eva vil alltid v\u00e6re min kone. ''Verdens Gang'' (October 28).] {{in lang|no}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nOdd B\u00f8rretzen won the [[Herman Wildenvey Poetry Award]] in 2005.<ref>[http://litteraturivestfold.origo.no/-/bulletin/show/740966_wildenveyprisen-2012?ref=checkpoint Wildenveyprisen 2012. 2012. ''Litteratur i Vestfold'' (June 6).]</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n{{commons}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|id=0127228}}\n\n{{Portal |Children's literature}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Borretzen, Odd}}\n[[Category:1926 births]]\n[[Category:2012 deaths]]\n[[Category:Norwegian children's writers]]\n[[Category:Norwegian dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Norwegian illustrators]]\n[[Category:Spellemannprisen winners]]\n[[Category:Leonard Statuette winners]]\n[[Category:Deaths from pneumonia]]\n[[Category:20th-century Norwegian dramatists and playwrights]]\n\n\n{{Norway-artist-stub}}\n{{illustrator-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "duplicate categorization; already in subcat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Odd_B%C3%B8rretzen"}
{"title_page": "1971 1. divisjon", "text_new": "{{Infobox football league season\n| competition                = [[Eliteserien|1. divisjon]]\n| season                     = 1971\n| winners                    = [[Rosenborg BK|Rosenborg]]<br />3rd title\n| relegated                  = [[Frigg Oslo FK|Frigg]]\n| continentalcup1            = [[1972\u201373 European Cup|European Cup]]\n| continentalcup1 qualifiers = [[Rosenborg BK|Rosenborg]]\n| continentalcup2            = [[1972\u201373 European Cup Winners' Cup|Cup Winners' Cup]]\n| continentalcup2 qualifiers = [[Fredrikstad FK|Fredrikstad]]\n| continentalcup3            = [[1972\u201373 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]]\n| continentalcup3 qualifiers = [[FK Lyn|Lyn]]<br>[[Viking FK|Viking]]\n| matches                    = 90\n| total goals                = 252\n| league topscorer           = [[Jan Fuglset]]<br/>(17 goals)\n| biggest home win           = {{no break|Lyn 7\u20131 Frigg}}<br><small>(26 April 1971)</small><br>{{no break|Viking 6\u20130 Fredrikstad}}<br><small>(17 June 1971)</small><br>{{no break|[[Sarpsborg FK]] 7\u20131 Frigg}}<br><small>(11 August 1971)</small><br>{{no break|Fredrikstad 7\u20131 Frigg}}<br><small>(17 October 1971)</small>\n| biggest away win           = {{no break|Frigg 0\u20135 [[IL H\u00f8dd|H\u00f8dd]]}}<br><small>(10 October 1971)</small>\n| highest scoring            = {{no break|Lyn 7\u20131 Frigg}}<br><small>(26 April 1971)</small><br>{{no break|[[Sarpsborg FK]] 7\u20131 Frigg}}<br><small>(11 August 1971)</small><br>{{no break|Fredrikstad 7\u20131 Frigg}}<br><small>(17 October 1971)</small>\n| longest wins               = Viking<br/>(5 games)\n| longest unbeaten           = Lyn<br/>(12 games)\n| longest winless            = H\u00f8dd<br/>(11 games)\n| longest losses             = Frigg<br/>H\u00f8dd<br/>(4 games)\n| highest attendance         = 15,200<br/>{{nobreak|Rosenborg 0\u20130 Str\u00f8msgodset}}<br/><small>(13 October 1971)</small>\n| lowest attendance          = 1,000<br/>{{nobreak|H\u00f8dd 4\u20131 [[HamKam]]}}<br/><small>(6 October 1971)</small>\n| average attendance         = 6,578 {{increase}} 16.7%\n| prevseason                 = [[1970 1. divisjon|1970]]\n| nextseason                 = [[1972 1. divisjon|1972]]\n}}\nThe '''1971 [[Eliteserien|1. divisjon]]''' was the 26th completed season of top division [[association football|football]] in [[Norway]].\n\n==Overview==\nIt was contested by 10 teams, and [[Rosenborg BK]] won the championship, their third league title.\n\nOnly one team was relegated this season due to the league's extension to 12 teams ahead of the [[1972 Norwegian First Division|1972]] season.\n\n==Teams and locations==\n:''Note: Table lists in alphabetical order.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" border=\"1\"\n|-\n! Team\n!{{Tooltip| Ap. | Appearances in top divisions of Norwegian football}}\n! Location\n|-\n| [[SK Brann|Brann]]\n| align=\"center\"| '''19'''\n| [[Bergen]]\n|-\n| [[Fredrikstad FK|Fredrikstad]]\n| align=\"center\"| '''26'''\n| [[Fredrikstad]]\n|-\n| [[Frigg Oslo FK|Frigg]]\n| align=\"center\"| '''14'''\n| [[Oslo]]\n|-\n| [[HamKam]]\n| align=\"center\"| '''3'''\n| [[Hamar]]\n|-\n| [[IL H\u00f8dd|H\u00f8dd]]\n| align=\"center\"| '''4'''\n| [[Ulsteinvik]]\n|-\n| [[Lyn Fotball|Lyn]]\n| align=\"center\"| '''18'''\n| [[Oslo]]\n|-\n| [[Rosenborg BK|Rosenborg]]\n| align=\"center\"| '''9'''\n| [[Trondheim]]\n|-\n| [[Sarpsborg FK]]\n| align=\"center\"| '''21'''\n| [[Sarpsborg]]\n|-\n| [[Str\u00f8msgodset Toppfotball|Str\u00f8msgodset]]\n| align=\"center\"| '''6'''\n| [[Drammen]]\n|-\n| [[Viking FK|Viking]]\n| align=\"center\"| '''24'''\n| [[Stavanger]]\n|}\n\n==League table==\n<onlyinclude>{{#invoke:sports table|main|style=WDL\n|res_col_header=QR\n|winpoints=2\n\n|team1=ROS|name_ROS=[[Rosenborg BK|Rosenborg]]\n|team2=LYN|name_LYN=[[FK Lyn|Lyn]]\n|team3=VIK|name_VIK=[[Viking FK|Viking]]\n|team4=FFK|name_FFK=[[Fredrikstad FK|Fredrikstad]]\n|team5=STR|name_STR=[[Str\u00f8msgodset IF|Str\u00f8msgodset]]\n|team6=HAM|name_HA